## Overview
Ethnography is a research method used to understand human behavior in its natural setting by immersing oneself into the community being studied.

## Purpose
The purpose of ethnography is to gain a deep understanding of how cultures work and affect people, allowing for the design and development of experiments that take into account these cultural nuances.

## How it works
Ethnography involves conducting immersion visits, collective actions, crowd mapping, field visits, interviews, and other data collection methods to gather information about human behavior in its natural setting. The researcher then analyzes this data to identify patterns and insights that can inform the design of experiments or interventions.

## Requirements
To effectively use ethnography for R&D purposes, researchers need strong data collection skills, adaptive capacity, and an understanding of different cultures and cultural settings.

## Reflections
When using ethnography, it's essential to be aware of one's own biases and to interpret the data from the perspective of the people being studied. This requires a high degree of empathy and understanding of the cultural context.

## Related methods (if any)
Ethnography is often used in conjunction with other methods such as Behavioral Insights, data collection, Solutions Mapping, and explore.
